title: Barrm Birrm Native Plants Riddells Creek

items.title: Pterostylis concinna
items.content_text: Photo shows the brown, notched labellum which distinguishes Pterostylis concinna from P. nana.

items.title: Pterostylis concinna
items.content_text: New species record for Barrm Birrm, Riddells Creek and the Macedon Range. One clump of about 1m diameter.

items.title: Cassytha pubescens s.s.
items.content_text: New species record for Barrm Birrm.

items.title: Acacia genistifolia
items.content_text: Not in flower (one flower remaining on each plant in BB). Following these plants all year and they have been flowering Mar-Jul.

items.title: Caladenia praecox
items.content_text: First plants of the season. One seen in flower 5 days ago.

items.title: Epacris impressa var. impressa
items.content_text: Pink with white tips.

items.title: Asplenium flabellifolium
items.content_text: Only grows on Barrm Birrm on rare outcrops of conglomerate rock.

items.title: Pelargonium rodneyanum
items.content_text: One plant flowering among hundreds.

items.title: Acacia genistifolia
items.content_text: One of only a few plants known in the Macedon Range - all are on Barrm Birrm.

items.title: Hypericum gramineum spp. agg.
items.content_text: Lots of these flowering at this spot.

items.title: Acacia genistifolia
items.content_text: Lovely old spreading Spreading Wattle. Note trunk of the plant in front left of 2nd pic.

items.title: Acacia dealbata subsp. dealbata
items.content_text: Enjoyed the green new growth contrasting with the grey older foliage.

items.title: Ozothamnus ferrugineus
items.content_text: About 6 plants on the Gap Road roadside. New species record for Barrm Birrm.

items.title: Acacia melanoxylon
items.content_text: Lovely 'semi-bonsaied' specimen.

items.title: Acacia gunnii
items.content_text: Goes red on BB after flowering.

items.title: Amphirhoe spp., Bursaria spinosa subsp. spinosa
Acacia genistifolia
items.content_text: Only 2(maybe 3) plants known in Riddells Creek. Photo taken with old iPhone.

items.title: Microseris walteri, Vanessa kershawi
items.content_text: unknown date - would be October or early November at this location.

items.title: Acacia implexa
items.content_text: Waited for this to flower since January. Wasn't in flower when I looked 7 days ago. 3 young plants (maybe 2 years old) - this species not recorded on Barrm Birrm until last year.

items.title: Acacia genistifolia
items.content_text: Young plants aren't flowering yet on Barrm Birrm but this wonderful old plant is having no trouble with the dry conditions.

items.title: Acacia leprosa var. uninervia, Peltoschema orphana
items.content_text: What looks like Fireblight Beetle attacking Acacia leprosa. All plants at this spot seem to be dead or seriously damaged. Two individuals photographed.

items.title: Thelymitra juncifolia
items.content_text: Tiny flowers (slightly smaller than $2 coin) seems to rule out T. ixioides. Both species have been recorded in the general area.

items.title: Kennedia prostrata
items.content_text: Great displays this year.

items.title: Carex appressa
items.content_text: 3-angled stem, broad leaves.

items.title: Viola hederacea sensu Thiele & Prober
items.content_text: Purple in bud. All flowers fully open. Strong purple colour in flower centre. Relatively short peduncles. See 7479 for comparison with new species.

items.title: Viola spp.
items.content_text: White in bud. Only one flower 'open' (remainder 'closed' & nodding) on this warm day (flowers open more on hotter days). Light purple venation in flower centre. Relatively long peduncles. See 7480 for comparison with Viola hederacea.

items.title: Hardenbergia violacea
items.content_text: Great displays.

items.title: Clematis microphylla s.s.
items.content_text: Male flowers being buzzed by Hover Flies.

items.title: Clematis microphylla s.s.
items.content_text: Female and male plants growing together - female shown here, male in next observation.

items.title: Cassytha glabella f. dispar
items.content_text: Locally quite rare in Riddells Creek. Currently heavy with fruit. Growing on Davesia leptophylla.

items.title: Dipodium roseum s.s.
items.content_text: This is the most unusual 'out-of-season' flowering plant I've seen this wet winter.

items.title: Hardenbergia violacea
items.content_text: First Hardenbergia flowers of the season in Barrm Birrm.

items.title: Acacia verticillata subsp. verticillata
items.content_text: Most plants aren't flowering yet.

items.title: Acacia dealbata subsp. dealbata
items.content_text: Most plants aren't flowering yet.

items.title: Acacia nanodealbata
items.content_text: Most plants aren't flowering yet.

items.title: Epacris impressa var. impressa
items.content_text: Epacris impressa pretty much doenn't occur at lower altitudes than this on Barrm Birrm.

items.title: Correa reflexa var. reflexa
items.content_text: Plants flowering in profusion.

items.title: Daviesia leptophylla
items.content_text: About 5% of plants flowering out of season.

items.title: Cassytha glabella f. dispar
items.content_text: Parasitic on Daviesia leptophylla.

items.title: Acacia genistifolia
items.content_text: Magnificent old specimen showing spreading trunk. One young plant growing nearby and only 1-2 other plants on Barrm Birrm - probably needs a fire to regenerate here. Location approximate.

items.title: Acacia implexa
items.content_text: 3 plants, each 6ft tall. New species record for Barrm Birrm.

items.title: Correa reflexa var. reflexa
items.content_text: With a few Daviesia leptophylla flowering out of season.

items.title: Dianella revoluta var. revoluta
items.content_text: Just the one or two plants with flowers out of season.

items.title: Acacia genistifolia
items.content_text: Flowers mostly Feb-Oct.

items.title: Carex breviculmis
items.content_text: New species for Barrm Birrm. It has come up in an area where gorse was removed two years ago.

items.title: Schoenus apogon
items.content_text: New species for Barrm Birrm. Thousands have come up after the rain over the past two seasons.

items.title: Centrolepis strigosa subsp. strigosa
items.content_text: New species for Barrm Birrm, Riddells Creek and the Macedon Range (one record on FIS at Woodend Racecourse). Came up after clearing a large patch of gorse 2 years ago.

items.title: Acacia leprosa var. uninervia, Acacia stricta
items.content_text: Shows differences in venation, leaf tip, peduncles & leaf pits on leprosa. Both species were in flower, not shown, & occur at this approx location.

items.title: Clematis microphylla s.s.
items.content_text: 9 leaflets throughout the plant = C. microphylla s.s.

items.title: Clematis microphylla s.s.
items.content_text: 9 leaflets.

items.title: Hovea heterophylla
items.content_text: Poor quality photo - taken on iPhone3. First flower of the season. iPhone geotag was a long way out!

items.title: Cheilanthes sieberi subsp. sieberi, Themeda triandra
Cryptandra amara s.s.
items.content_text: First flowers of the season. Many plants on the Barrm Birrm side seem to have start flowering whereas most on the Conglomerate Gully side are in bud.

items.title: Juncus planifolius
items.content_text: Moist area in a very wet season. These plants varied in height from 30-80cm tall.

items.title: Grevillea alpina
items.content_text: First flowers of the season. Quite a few plants with a few flowers.

items.title: Stylidium armeria subsp. pilosifolium
items.content_text: Only a few plants. My guess is the adjoining farm may have had many plants originally because plants have now been found all around its border.

items.title: Stylidium armeria subsp. pilosifolium
items.content_text: Only a few plants.

items.title: Cheilanthes sieberi subsp. sieberi
items.content_text: Lots of plants on a small rocky area in the forest.

items.title: Lomandra filiformis
items.content_text: Good population of the grey-leaved form of Lomandra filiformis. Leaves range from 2mm wide upwards. Right on the imaginary border of Barrm Birrm and Conglomerate Gully.

items.title: Eucalyptus obliqua
items.content_text: Coming to the end of its flowering. Strong, sweet smell when close to flowers.

items.title: 9 ids
items.content_text: Brief survey of plants in flower in early January in a good rain season. Walked up nice track to the dam (not the most northerly track - next track down).
